{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Christ, the Messenger | image = Swami_Vivekananda_1893_Scanned_Image.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | author = [[Swami Vivekananda]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | release_number = | subject = | genre = | set_in = | published = 1900 | publisher = The Vedanta Centre, Boston | publisher2 = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda/Volume 4/Lectures and Discourses/Christ, the Messenger | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }}
'''''Christ, the Messenger''''' was a lecture delivered by [[Swami Vivekananda]] in [[Los Angeles]], California in January 1900. In the same year the lecture was published as a book by The Vedanta Centre, Boston. In his lecture Vivekananda attempted to analyze the life and messages of [[Jesus]] through [[Vedanta]].{{Sfn|Jongeneel|2009|p=192}}{{Sfn|Bhide|2008|p=39}}{{Sfn|Burke|1973|p=204}}{{Sfn|Arangassery|1999|p=22}}
== Synopsis == In his lecture Vivekananda has compared the entire human existence to an ocean, where an individual's life is like waves. He has compared human lives with the waves rising on the ocean, and then falling down. Jesus is like a big wave that comes very rarely. Vivekananda called Jesus "The great soul, the Messenger."{{Sfn|Vivekananda|2015|p=552}}<ref name=Christ>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vedanta.com/store/christ.php|title=Christ the Messenger: The Complete Text from the booklet Christ the Messenger|accessdate=27 December 2015|publisher=Vedanta Press and catalog}}</ref>
==Lecture== Vivekananda in his lecture, while presenting a balanced view on Christianity, also mentioned its drawbacks. He based his arguments on his [[Hindu philosophy]] of [[Vedanta]] which was that there was only one reality in the world which was the [[Brahman]] which subsumes the core aspects of the human being, the [[Ātman (Hinduism)|Atman]]. He said that in [[Christ]] the most profound knowledge is made available to us which is the identity of human beings and God.{{Sfn|Schouten|2008|p=92}}
Vivekananda said that the land where he was born, in a race which was the land of the Jews, was in strife with stagnation and suffering {{Sfn|Saraf|2012|p=128}} and due to differences between [[Pharisees]] and [[Sadducees]]. This caused "about the very impetus which came out at the other end as the gigantic brain of Jesus of Nazareth." The land was in the Asian region, which has lofty mountains touching the sky and large swathes of desert land.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|2015|pp=551&ndash;58}}<ref name=Christ/>
Vivekananda looked at Jesus Christ from the prescriptive of an Orientalist as He was born in the region of Asia and thus called Jesus as an "Oriental of Orientals," though his physical features of blue eyes and yellow hair was a picture presented by [[Europeans]].{{Sfn|Schouten|2008|p=92}}{{Sfn|Jongeneel|2009|p=192}} He made a comparison of the two religious beliefs of the west and the east - the former as a [[Greek culture]] of politics dominated by God of human passions. While the culture of the east was for what is beyond that which exists. All divine prophets were oriental like Jesus. Jesus was practical in the oriental sense.{{Sfn|Jongeneel|2009|p=192}}
Vivekananda, in his lecture, as an analogy, drew attention to the wise sayings of [[Krishna]], the Hindu god, from the [[Bhagavad Gita]] that: "Wherever thou findeth a great soul of immense power and purity struggling to raise humanity, know that he is born of My Splendour, that I am working there through him," and said that in addition to finding God in [[Jesus of Nazareth]], let us find Him through all those prophets, the man-Gods, he preceded, succeeded or yet to follow Jesus, as they are all reincarnations of the same God whom we all hold in great reverence.{{Sfn|Bhide|2008|p=39}}
Vivekananda emphasized that it was essential to worship God as man, and such a god man was Christ and hence not to give up his worship as "all our ideas of God are concentrated there". However, he mentioned the drawback of Christianity as their refusal to consider other reincarnations of God in other religions. [[Buddha]] before Christ was a reincarnation of God and like him there were many more.{{Sfn|Bhide|2008|p=39}}{{Sfn|Saraf|2012|p=128}}
Vivekananda spoke that Jesus's message to all was to pursue the ideal and achieve it in one's own way, irrespective of whether one gives credit for His teachings or not. Religion is not traded like a shop owner. What is taught by Jesus is only truth, which is nobody's proprietorial right. "Truth is God Himself."{{Sfn|Saraf|2012|p=128}}{{Sfn|Vivekananda|2015|pp=551&ndash;558}}
In his "oeuvre" Vivekananda said that Christ was "intensely practical" and offered a practical religion. A significant reference made by Vivekananda was to the saying from the [[Bible]] (Mathew 8:20, Luke 9:58) to stress the message that renouncing worldly matters is the way to salvation: "Foxes have holes and birds of the air have nests, but the son of Man has no place to lay his head."{{Sfn|Schouten|2008|p=94}}
== Publication == The lecture was first published as a book by The Vedanta Centre, Boston in 1900. It was also included in ''[[The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda]]'' ''Volume IV''.<ref name="Vivekananda1900">{{cite book|last=Vivekananda|first=Swami|title=Christ, the messenger: lecture delivered by Swami Vivekananda at Los Angeles, California, 1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ni4-AAAAYAAJ|date=1900|publisher=The Vedanta Centre|pages=4–11}}</ref> The publication is based on the stenographic records of his lectures delivered in Los Angeles in January 1900 to a large audience{{Sfn|Schouten|2008|p=93}} of Christians.{{Sfn|Bhide|2008|p=39}}
