'''Muhammad of Tabaristan''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: محمد) was the ruler of the [[Bavand dynasty]] from 1249 to 1271. He was the son and successor of [[Ardashir II of Tabaristan]]. 

== Biography ==
Muhammad had close relations with his ally the [[Paduspanid]] Shahragim, and even married his daughter. During the reign of the [[Ilkhanid]] [[Abaqa Khan]], Muhammad and Shahrigam were ordered to aid the Ilkhanids in their siege of fortress of [[Gerdkuh]], which was held by the [[Ismailites]]. Muhammad and Shahragim disobeyed, however. Abaqa Khan responded by invading [[Mazandaran]]. The two kings were then forgiven. Muhammad then joined the armies of the Ilkhanid, but was shortly arrested because of his recklessness. After hearing about Muhammad's imprisonment, Shahragim revolted against Abaqa, which resulted in the execution of Muhammad, who was succeeded by his brother [[Ali II of Tabaristan]].

