{{Culture of the Philippines}}
[[File:St Peter and Paul Cathedral.jpg|thumb|[[Tuguegarao Cathedral|St Peter's Metropolitan Cathedral]] in [[Tuguegarao]]]]
'''Religion in the Philippines''' is marked by a majority of people being adherents of the [[Christianity|Christian]] faith.<ref name=NSO2014>[https://www.census.gov.ph/sites/default/files/2014%20PIF.pdf Philippines in Figures : 2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728203542/http://www.census.gov.ph/sites/default/files/2014%20PIF.pdf |date=2014-07-28 }}, [[Philippine Statistics Authority]].</ref> At least 92% of the population is Christian; about 81% belong to the [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholic Church]] while about 11% belong to [[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestant]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]], [[Restorationist]] and [[Independent Catholic]] denominations, such as [[Iglesia Filipina Independiente]], [[Iglesia ni Cristo]], [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]], [[United Church of Christ in the Philippines]] and [[Evangelicalism in the Philippines|Evangelicals]].<ref name=NSO2014 /> Officially, the Philippines is a [[secular state|secular nation]], with the [[1987 Constitution|Constitution]] guaranteeing [[separation of church and state]], and requiring the government to respect all religious beliefs equally.

According to national religious surveys, about 5.6% of the population of the Philippines is [[Muslim]], making [[Islam]] the second largest religion in the country. However, A 2012 estimate by the [[National Commission on Muslim Filipinos]] (NCMF) stated that there were 10.7 million Muslims,  or approximately 11 percent of the total population.<ref name=2013ifr>{{cite report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2013/eap/222161.htm|title=Philippines|at=SECTION I. RELIGIOUS DEMOGRAPHY|work=2013 Report on International Religious Freedom|date=July 28, 2014|publisher=United States Department of State|quote=The 2000 survey states that Islam is the largest minority religion, constituting approximately 5 percent of the population. A 2012 estimate by the National Commission on Muslim Filipinos (NCMF), however, states that there are 10.7 million Muslims, which is approximately 11 percent of the total population.|access-date=2017-06-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625162207/https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2013/eap/222161.htm#|archivedate=2017-06-25|deadurl=no|df=}}</ref> Most Muslims live in parts of Mindanao, Palawan, and the Sulu Archipelago – an area known as [[Bangsamoro (political entity)|Bangsamoro]] or the [[Moro (Philippines)|Moro]] region.<ref>[http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=472375&publicationSubCategoryId=205 RP closer to becoming observer-state in Organization of Islamic Conference] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603143753/http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=472375&publicationSubCategoryId=205 |date=2016-06-03 }}. (2009-05-29). ''[[The Philippine Star]]''. Retrieved 2009-07-10, "Eight million Muslim Filipinos, representing 10 percent of the total Philippine population, ...".</ref> Some have migrated into urban and rural areas in different parts of the country. Most Muslim Filipinos practice [[Sunni Islam]] according to the [[Shafi'i]] school.<ref name=McAmis>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=59PnSwurWj8C&pg=PA18|title=Malay Muslims: The History and Challenge of Resurgent Islam in Southeast Asia|author=McAmis, Robert Day|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|year=2002|pages=18–24, 53–61|isbn=0-8028-4945-8|accessdate=2010-01-07}}</ref> There are some [[Ahmadiyya]] Muslims in the country.<ref name="R Michael Feener, Terenjit Sevea 144">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2MyHnPaox9MC&pg=PA144&dq&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zMGSU6nvIsmM7QaY-YCoAg&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Islamic Connections: Muslim Societies in South and Southeast Asia |author1=R Michael Feener |author2=Terenjit Sevea |page=144 |accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref>

[[Indigenous religious beliefs of the Philippines|Philippine traditional religions]] are still practiced by an estimated 2% of the population,<ref name="cia-rp" /><ref name=pew>[http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/philippines/religious_demography Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project: Philippines] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708193611/http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/philippines/religious_demography# |date=2014-07-08 }}. [[Pew Research Center]]. 2010.</ref> made up of many indigenous peoples, tribal groups, and people who have reverted into traditional religions from Catholic/Christian or Islamic religions. These religions are often [[syncretic religion|syncretized]] with Christianity and Islam. [[Animism]], [[folk religion]], and [[shamanism]] remain present as undercurrents of mainstream religion, through the ''[[albularyo]]'', the ''[[babaylan]]'', and the ''[[manghihilot]]''. [[Buddhism in the Philippines|Buddhism]] is practiced by 2% of the populations by the [[Japanese people|Japanese-Filipino community]],<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.buddhist-tourism.com/countries/philippines/buddhism-in-philippines.html|title=Buddhism in Philippines, Guide to Philippines Buddhism, Introduction to Philippines Buddhism, Philippines Buddhism Travel|publisher=}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=cia-rp>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rp.html|title=The World Factbook — Central Intelligence Agency|publisher=|access-date=2012-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719222229/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rp.html#|archive-date=2015-07-19|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref name=pew /><ref name="globalreligiousfutures.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/philippines/religious_demography#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|title=Philippines – Pew-Templeton Global Religious Futures Project|publisher=|access-date=2014-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708193611/http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/philippines/religious_demography#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|archive-date=2014-07-08|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> and together with [[Taoism]] and [[Chinese folk religion]] is also dominant in Chinese communities. There are smaller number of followers of [[Sikhs]], [[Hinduism in the Philippines|Hinduism]],<ref name=cia-rp /><ref name=pew /><ref name="globalreligiousfutures.org"/> and [[History of the Jews in the Philippines|Judaism]], and [[Baha'i Faith in the Philippines|Baha'i]].<ref>[http://www.adherents.com/largecom/com_bahai.html The Largest Baha'i Communities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019165843/http://www.adherents.com/largecom/com_bahai.html# |date=2008-10-19 }}. (2005-09-30). Retrieved 2010-04-26 from www.adherents.com.</ref> More than 10% of the population is [[Irreligion in the Philippines|non-religious]], with the percentage of non-religious people overlapping with various faiths, as the vast majority of the non-religious select a religion in the Census for nominal purposes.<ref name=cia-rp /><ref name=pew /><ref>Note: The Irreligious population is taken from the Catholic majority. The 65% is from the Filipino American population which have a more accurate demographic count sans the Muslim population of the Philippines.
