=== Members Church of God in Jesus Christ Worldwide ===
Members Church of God in Jesus Christ Worldwide (also known as ''Miembro de la Iglesia de Dios en Todo el Mundo Inc.'') is an independent Christian organization with headquarters in the Philippines led by Wilfredo "Bro. Willy" Santiago, a former Bible reader for Members Church of God International (MCGI). Willy Santiago was excommunicated from MCGI due to various violations. Santiago is currently building a new church headquarters in Malolos, Bulacan.

=== The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints ===
{{Main|The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in the Philippines}}
[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) in the Philippines was founded during the Spanish–American War in 1898. Two men from [[Utah]] who were members of the United States artillery battery, and who were also set apart as missionaries by the Church before they left the United States, preached while stationed in the Philippines. Missionary work picked up after World War II, and in 1961 the Church was officially registered in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.lds.org/liahona/2006/09/news-of-the-church/new-temple-announcement-answers-members-prayers |title=News of the Church: New Temple Announcement Answers Members' Prayers |date=September 2006 |journal=[[Liahona (magazine)|Liahona]] |accessdate=2008-11-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115214157/http://www.lds.org/liahona/2006/09/news-of-the-church/new-temple-announcement-answers-members-prayers# |archive-date=2013-11-15 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> In 1969, the Church had spread to eight major islands and had the highest number of baptisms of any area in the Church. A temple was built in 1984 which located in Quezon City and another in Cebu City, completed in 2010. Membership was 710,764 in 2015.<ref name=NewsroomFacts>{{cite web |url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/facts-and-statistics/country/philippines/ |title=Facts and Statistics – Philippines |publisher=Newsroom – The Church of Jesus Christ of the Latter-Day Saints |accessdate=May 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421172911/http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/facts-and-statistics/country/philippines/# |archive-date=2015-04-21 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref>

=== Other Christians ===
* The [[Bible Student movement]], from which [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] later developed, was introduced to the Philippines in 1912, when the president of the [[Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|Watch Tower Society]], [[Charles Taze Russell]], gave a talk at the former [[Manila Grand Opera House]].<ref>2003 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses, p.154</ref> In 1993, a [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] case involving the Witnesses resulted in the reversal of an earlier 1959 Supreme Court decision and in upholding "the right of children of Jehovah's Witnesses to refrain from saluting the [[Flag of the Philippines|flag]], reciting the [[Panatang Makabayan|pledge of allegiance]], and singing [[Lupang Hinirang|the national anthem]]."<ref>''Awake!'' January 8, 1994, p.22</ref><ref>[http://www.chanrobles.com/scdecisions/jurisprudence1993/mar1993/gr_95770_1993.php G.R. No. 95770 March 1, 1993] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101063145/http://www.chanrobles.com/scdecisions/jurisprudence1993/mar1993/gr_95770_1993.php# |date=2015-01-01 }}. Chanrobles.com. Retrieved on 2012-03-27.</ref> As of 2015, there were officially 201,001 active members in the Philippines in 3,156 congregations nationwide. Their 2013 observance of the annual [[Jehovah's Witnesses practices#Memorial of Christ's death|Memorial of Christ's death]] attracted an attendance of 543,282 in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/publications/books/2014-yearbook/|title=2014 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watch Tower Society|access-date=2014-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716130444/http://www.jw.org/en/publications/books/2014-yearbook/#|archive-date=2014-07-16|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>{{fv|date=November 2018|reason=note original placement at https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Religion_in_the_Philippines&diff=prev&oldid=609549431 in support of different figures}}
* [[Kingdom of Jesus Christ (church)|The Kingdom of Jesus Christ, the Name Above Every Name]] was founded by Pastor [[Apollo Quiboloy|Apollo C. Quiboloy]] on 1 September 1985. Pastor Quiboloy claims to be the "Appointed" [[Son of God]], that salvation is through him, that he is the residence of the [[God the Father]] and that he restores the [[Kingdom of God]] in the gentile settings.
* The [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]] was founded by [[Ellen G. White]], which is best known for its teaching that Saturday, the seventh day of the week, is the [[Sabbath and Seventh-day Adventism|Sabbath]], and that the [[second advent]] of Christ is imminent. Colloquially called ''Sabadístas'' by outsiders, Filipino Adventists numbered 571,653 in 88,706 congregations as of 2007, and with an annual membership growth rate of 5.6%.<ref>[http://adventistatlas.org/ViewCountry.asp?CtryCode=ph Philippines] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224544/http://adventistatlas.org/ViewCountry.asp?CtryCode=ph# |date=2011-07-24 }}, [http://adventistatlas.org/ Adventist Atlas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622212959/http://www.adventistatlas.org/# |date=2011-06-22 }}.</ref>
* [[United Pentecostal Church International]] (Oneness) originated in the United States as an offshoot of the Pentecostal movements in the 1920s. The church is a proponent of the belief of modalism to describe God, and is [[non-trinitarian]] in its conception of God.
* [[Jesus Christ To God be the Glory]] (Friends Again) was founded by Luis Ruíz Santos in 1988.
* [[Churches of Christ]] (Churches of Christ 33 AD/the Stone-Campbellites) is a restorationist movement that distinctly believes in a set of steps or ways to attain salvation, among of which is prerequisite [[immersion baptism]].
* [[True Jesus Church]] a "oneness" movement that started in the People's Republic of China.
* [[Jesus is Our Shield Worldwide Ministries]] (commonly known as ''Oras ng Himala'', "Hour of Miracle[s]") was founded by Renato D. Carillo, who claims to be the end-times apostle.
* [[Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]] (UCKG Help Center) was founded by Edir Macedo in 1977 in Brazil.
* [[Unification Church]], founded by [[Sun Myung Moon]] in what is today South Korea.
*[[Jesus is I.L Church]], founded by [[I.L Noval]] in 2011. The church has exponentially expanded since then and now has about 76,000 members.

== Islam ==
{{Main|Islam in the Philippines|List of mosques in the Philippines}}
{{See also|Moro (ethnic group)}}
[[File:Old Mosque Lanao Del Sur Philippines.jpg|thumb|255x255px|Old Maranaw style mosque in Taraka, Lanao Del Sur. The Philippine mosque pagoda-style in now considered an endangered architectural style in the country as majority of Philippine mosques were converted into Arabian-style mosques in the 18th-20th centuries.]]
[[File:Golden Mosque, Manila.jpg|thumb|Manila Golden Mosque]]
[[Islam]] reached the Philippines in the 14th century with the arrival of [[Muslim]] traders from the Persian Gulf, Southern India, and their followers from several [[Sultan#Southeast & East Asia|sultanate]] governments in [[Maritime Southeast Asia]]. Islam's predominance reached all the way to the shores of [[Manila Bay]], home to several Muslim kingdoms. During the Spanish conquest, Islam had a rapid decline as the predominant monotheistic faith in the Philippines as a result of the introduction of Roman Catholicism by Spanish missionaries and via the [[Spanish Inquisition]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Laforteza|first=Elaine Marie Carbonell|title=The Somatechnics of Whiteness and Race: Colonialism and Mestiza Privilege|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5tS1CwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-01516-1|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=5tS1CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA35&dq=%22spanish+inquisition%22 35–36]}}</ref> The [[Moro (ethnic group)|southern Filipino tribes]] were among the few indigenous Filipino communities that resisted Spanish rule and conversions to Roman Catholicism. The vast majority of [[Islam in Philippines|Muslims in Philippines]] follow [[Sunni Islam]] of [[Shafi]] school of [[jurisprudence]], with small [[Shia Islam|Shiite]] and [[Ahmadiyya]] minorities.<ref name="R Michael Feener, Terenjit Sevea 144" /> Islam is the oldest recorded [[Monotheism|monotheistic]] religion in the Philippines.

{{as of|2015}}. According to the [[Philippine Statistics Authority]],<ref name="PSA-2015PSY" /> the [[Muslim]] population of Philippines in 2015 was 5.57%. However, a 2012 estimate by the [[National Commission on Muslim Filipinos]] (NCMF) stated that there were 10.7 million Muslims,  or approximately 11 percent of the total population.<ref name="2013ifr"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2004/35425.htm|title=Philippines|publisher=|access-date=2018-05-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026053752/https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2004/35425.htm#|archive-date=2017-10-26|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>

=== History ===
{{Main|History of the Philippines}}
[[File:Kaum Purnah Mosque.JPG|thumb|Mosque in [[Isabela, Basilan|Isabela City]].]]
In 1380 [[Makhdum Karim|Karim ul' Makhdum]] the first Arabian trader reached the [[Sulu Archipelago]] and [[Jolo]] in the Philippines and through trade throughout the island established Islam in the country. In 1390 the [[Minangkabau people|Minangkabau]]'s Prince [[Rajah Baguinda]] and his followers preached Islam on the islands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://majalah.tempointeraktif.com/id/arsip/1990/06/23/SEL/mbm.19900623.SEL18854.id.html |title=Kerinduan orang-orang moro |publisher=TEMPO- Majalah Berita Mingguan |date=June 23, 1990|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219025658/http://majalah.tempointeraktif.com/id/arsip/1990/06/23/SEL/mbm.19900623.SEL18854.id.html|archivedate=2012-02-19}}</ref> The [[Sheik Karimal Makdum Mosque]] was the first mosque established in the Philippines on [[Simunul, Tawi-Tawi|Simunul]] in [[Mindanao]] in the 14th century. Subsequent settlements by Arab missionaries traveling to [[Malaysia]] and [[Indonesia]] helped strengthen Islam in the Philippines and each settlement was governed by a [[Datu]], [[Rajah]] and a [[Sultan]].

By the next century conquests had reached the [[Sulu]] islands in the southern tip of the [[Philippines]] where the population was animistic and they took up the task of converting the animistic population to Islam with renewed zeal. By the 15th century, half of [[Luzon]] (Northern Philippines) and the islands of [[Mindanao]] in the south had become subject to the various Muslim [[sultanates]] of [[Borneo]] and much of the population in the [[Mindanao|South]] were converted to Islam. However, the [[Visayas]] was largely dominated by [[Hinduism in the Philippines#Pre-contact period|Hindu]]-[[Buddhism in the Philippines#Pre-colonial period|Buddhist]] societies led by [[rajah]]s and [[Datu#Datu in Pre-colonial Principalities in the Visayas|datus]] who strongly resisted [[Islam]]. One reason could be due to the economic and political disasters prehispanic [[Moro Pirates|Muslim pirates]] from the Mindanao region bring during raids. These frequent attacks gave way to naming present-day [[Cebu]] as then-''Sugbo'' or scorched earth which was a defensive technique implemented by the [[Visayans]] so the pirates have nothing much to loot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cebueskrima.s5.com/custom3.html |title=A Rapid Journal Article Volume 10, No. 2 |publisher=Celestino C. Macachor |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120703210211/http://cebueskrima.s5.com/custom3.html |archivedate=July 3, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=504886 |title=The Aginid |publisher=Maria Eleanor Elape Valeros |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130208164315/http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=504886# |archive-date=2013-02-08 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

[[Moro people|Moro]] (derived from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word meaning ''Moors'') is the appellation inherited from the [[Spaniards]], for [[Filipino Muslims]] and [[Lumad|tribal groups]] of Mindanao. The Moros seek to establish an independent Islamic province in Mindanao to be named [[Moro people|Bangsamoro]]. The term ''Bangsamoro'' is a combination of an [[Old Malay language|Old Malay]] word meaning ''nation'' or ''state'' with the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word ''Moro''. A significant [[Moro rebellion]] occurred during the [[Philippine–American War]]. Conflicts and rebellion have continued in the Philippines from the pre-colonial period up to the [[Peace process with the Bangsamoro in the Philippines|present]].

=== Muslim Mindanao ===
{{Main|Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao}}
The Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM) comprises the [[Philippines]]' predominantly Muslim [[Provinces of the Philippines|provinces]], namely: [[Basilan]] (except [[Isabela, Basilan|Isabela City]]), [[Lanao del Sur]], [[Maguindanao]], [[Sulu]] and [[Tawi-Tawi]], and the [[Marawi City|Islamic City of Marawi]]. It is the only [[Regions of the Philippines|region]] with its own government. The regional capital is at [[Cotabato City]], although this [[Cities of the Philippines|city]] is outside of its jurisdiction.

== Judaism ==
{{Main|History of the Jews in the Philippines}}
Even since the 1590s some Jews fleeing from The Inquisition were recorded to have come to the Philippines. As of 2005, [[Philippine nationality law|Filipino]] [[Jews]] number at the very most 18,500 people. {{as of|2011}}, [[Metro Manila]] boasted the largest Jewish community in the Philippines{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} which, as of 2008, consisted of roughly 100 families.<ref name=jta>[http://www.jewishtimesasia.org/manila/269-manila-communities/576-philippines-jewish-community Philippines Jewish Community] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224105428/http://www.jewishtimesasia.org/manila/269-manila-communities/576-philippines-jewish-community# |date=2009-12-24 }} (May, 2008). Jewishtimesasia.org. Retrieved on 2015-01-24.</ref>

The country's only synagogue, Beth Yaacov, is located in [[Makati]].<ref name=jta /> There are other Jews elsewhere in the country,<ref name=jta /> but these are much fewer and almost all transients,<ref>Schlossberger, E. ''[http://www.feu-alumni.com/lifestyle.htm Cauliflower and Ketchup] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090729092850/http://www.feu-alumni.com/lifestyle.htm# |date=2009-07-29 }}''.</ref> either [[diplomat]]s or business envoys, and their existence is almost totally unknown in mainstream society. There are a few [[Israelis]] in Manila recruiting caregivers for Israel, some work in call centers, businessmen and a few other executives. A number are converts to Judaism.

== Hinduism ==
{{Main|Hinduism in the Philippines}}
The [[Srivijaya]] Empire and [[Majapahit Empire]] on what is now [[Malaysia]] and [[Indonesia]], introduced Hinduism and Buddhism to the islands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sanghapinoy.bravehost.com/history.htm|title=History of Buddhism|publisher=[http://sanghapinoy.bravehost.com/index.htm Buddhism in the Philippines]|accessdate=2008-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820111140/http://sanghapinoy.bravehost.com/history.htm#|archive-date=2008-08-20|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Ancient statues of Hindu-Buddhist gods have been found in the Philippines dating as far back as 600 to 1600 years from present.<ref>{{cite book|title=Some Aspects of Asia and Culture|publisher=Abhinav Publications|year=1986|last=Thakur|first=Upendra}}</ref>

The archipelagoes of Southeast Asia were under the influence of Hindu [[Tamil people]], [[Gujarati people]] and Indonesian traders through the ports of Malay-Indonesian islands. Indian religions, possibly an amalgamated version of Hindu-Buddhist arrived in Philippines archipelago in the 1st millennium, through the Indonesian kingdom of Srivijaya followed by [[Majapahit]]. Archeological evidence suggesting exchange of ancient spiritual ideas from India to the Philippines includes the 1.79 kilogram, 21 carat gold Hindu goddess Agusan (sometimes referred to as Golden Tara), found in Mindanao in 1917 after a storm and flood exposed its location.

Another gold artifact, from the Tabon caves in the island of Palawan, is an image of Garuda, the bird who is the mount of Vishnu. The discovery of sophisticated Hindu imagery and gold artifacts in Tabon caves has been linked to those found from Oc Eo, in the Mekong Delta in Southern Vietnam.<ref name=atnb>Anna T. N. Bennett (2009), [http://archeosciences.revues.org/2072 "Gold in early Southeast Asia"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514022330/http://archeosciences.revues.org/2072# |date=2015-05-14 }}, ''ArcheoSciences'', Volume 33, pp 99–107</ref> These archaeological evidence suggests an active trade of many specialized goods and gold between India and Philippines and coastal regions of Vietnam and China. Golden jewelry found so far include rings, some surmounted by images of [[Nandi (bull)|Nandi]] – the sacred bull, linked chains, inscribed gold sheets, gold plaques decorated with repoussé images of Hindu deities.<ref>Dang V.T. and Vu, Q.H., 1977. "The excavation at Giong Ca Vo site." ''Journal of Southeast Asian Archaeology'' 17: 30–37</ref>

Today Hinduism is largely confined to the Indian Filipinos and the [[expatriate]] Indian community. Theravada and Vajrayana Buddhism, are practiced by [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]], [[Sri Lanka]]n, [[Bamar|Burmese]] and [[Thai people|Thai]] nationals. There are Hindu temples in Manila, as well as in the provinces. There are temples also for [[Sikhism]], sometimes located near Hindu temples. The two Paco temples are well known, comprising a Hindu temple and a Sikh temple.

== Irreligion ==
{{Main|Irreligion in the Philippines}}{{See also|History of the Humanist Movement in the Philippines}}
Dentsu Communication Institute Inc., Research Centre for Japan said in 2006 that about 11% of the population are [[irreligious]].<ref name="dentsu">[http://www2.ttcn.ne.jp/~honkawa/9460.html Dentsu Communication Institute Inc., Research Centre for Japan (2006)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216055752/http://www2.ttcn.ne.jp/~honkawa/9460.html# |date=2015-02-16 }}{{ja icon}}</ref> Other sources put the number at less than 0.1%.<ref name="atlantic">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/03/new-atheists-philippines/518175/ |title=The New Atheists of the Philippines |last=French |first=Michael |date=March 5, 2017 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date=2017-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807233721/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/03/new-atheists-philippines/518175/# |archive-date=2017-08-07 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref>

In February 2009, [[Filipino Freethinkers]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Filipino Freethinkers Official Website|url=http://filipinofreethinkers.org|accessdate=2009-08-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706061444/http://filipinofreethinkers.org/#|archive-date=2011-07-06|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> was formed. Since 2011, the [[Philippine Atheists and Agnostics Society]] has held its OUT Campaigns in Rizal Park and Quezon Memorial Circle. Also it held two feeding programs "Good without Religion" in Bacoor, Cavite.<ref>[http://freethinker.co.uk/2011/04/28/the-pope%E2%80%99s-gonna-have-a-cow-catholic-philippines-gains-its-first-atheist-society/ Catholic Philippines gains its first atheist society] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701200357/http://freethinker.co.uk/2011/04/28/the-pope%E2%80%99s-gonna-have-a-cow-catholic-philippines-gains-its-first-atheist-society/# |date=2011-07-01 }}. Freethinker.co.uk. Retrieved on 2012-03-27.</ref> The society also is a member affiliate and associate of various international atheist organizations such as the [[Atheist Alliance International]], Institute for Science and Human Values, and the [[International Humanist and Ethical Union]], as one among secular organizations that promotes free thought and scientific development in the Philippines.

== Religion and politics ==
{{further|Freedom of religion in the Philippines}}
The 1987 Constitution of the Philippines declares: The separation of Church and State shall be inviolable. (Article II, Section 6), and, No law shall be made respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof. The free exercise and enjoyment of religious profession and worship, without discrimination or preference, shall forever be allowed. No religious test shall be required for the exercise of civil or political rights. (Article III, Section 5). Joaquin Bernas, a Filipino Jesuit specializing in constitutional law, acknowledges that there were complex issues that were brought to court and numerous attempts to use the separation of Church and State against the Roman Catholic Church, but he defends the statement, saying that "the fact that he [Marcos] tried to do it does not deny the validity of the separation of church and state".<ref>{{cite book|author=Joaquin G. Bernas|title=The Intent of the 1986 Constitution Writers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pVSGwAACAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Published & distributed by Rex Book Store|page=86}}</ref>

On April 28, 2004, the Philippines Supreme Court reversed the ruling of a lower court ordering five religious leaders to refrain from endorsing a candidate for elective office.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=flc1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=iSUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1803,21942553 Philippine Daily Inquirer]. News.google.com (2004-05-01). Retrieved on 2012-03-27.</ref><ref>[http://sc.judiciary.gov.ph/jurisprudence/2004/apr2004/159357.htm Velarde vs Social Justice Society : 159357 : April 28, 2004 : J. Panganiban : En Banc : Decision] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401210941/http://sc.judiciary.gov.ph/jurisprudence/2004/apr2004/159357.htm# |date=2012-04-01 }}. Sc.judiciary.gov.ph. Retrieved on 2012-03-27.</ref> Manila Judge Conception Alarcon-Vergara had ruled that the 
"head of a religious organization who influences or threatens to punish members could be held liable for coercion and violation of citizen's right to vote freely". The lawsuit filed by Social Justice Society party stated that "the Church's active participation in partisan politics, using the awesome voting strength of its faithful flock, will enable it to elect men to public office who will in turn be forever beholden to its leaders, enabling them to control the government".

They claimed that this violates the Philippine constitution's separation of Church and State clause. The named respondents were Roman Catholic Archbishop of Manila [[Luis Antonio Cardinal Tagle]], [[El Shaddai (movement)|El Shaddai Movement]] Leader [[Mike Velarde]], [[Iglesia ni Cristo]] Executive Minister [[Eduardo V. Manalo]] and [[Jesus Is Lord Church]] leader [[Eddie Villanueva]]. Manalo's Iglesia ni Cristo practices bloc voting. Former Catholic Archbishop [[Jaime Sin|Jaime Cardinal Sin]] had been instrumental in rallying support for the assumption to power of [[Corazon Aquino]] and [[Gloria Arroyo]]. Velarde supported [[Fidel V. Ramos]], [[Joseph Estrada]], [[Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo]] and [[Benigno Aquino III]] while Villanueva endorsed [[Fidel Ramos]] and [[Jose De Venecia]]. The [[papal nuncio]] agreed with the decision of the lower court<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Z48VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ogsEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6573,2463633 No role for Church in politics]. Manila Standard. June 22, 2003</ref> while the other respondents challenged the decision.<ref>Philip C. Tubeza [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eFU1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=fCUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2904,34794787 Iglesia appeals court ruling infringing on group's belief]. Philippine Daily Inquirer. July 20, 2003</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GVo1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=kyUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2577,53069 SC ruling sought on sect's vote]. Philippine Daily Inquirer. April 1, 2004</ref>

