'''Sesibi''' was a [[New Kingdom Egypt]]ian town the west bank of the [[Nile]], across from [[Delgo, Sudan]].<ref>Sophie Ibbotson, Max Lovell-Hoare Sudan: 2012 - Page 141 1841624136 "There are the remains of several ancient Egyptian temples between Kerma and Abri, all on the west bank of the Nile. This is ... SESIBI. The ruins of the New Kingdom Egyptian town of Sesibi are on the west bank of the Nile, across from Delgo."</ref> A temple was built there by [[Akhenaten]] who appointed a viceroy to maintain the structure, govern the local settlement, and secure traffic on the Nile.<ref>Jill Kamil Aswan and Abu Simbel: History and Guide 9774243218- Page 16 - 1993 "At nearby Sesibi, his successor Akhenaten built another temple. Viceroys were appointed in both locations to maintain these structures, govern the local communities, and ensure the regularity of the shipments northward. "</ref>
