[[File:Whitechapel Road, looking east - geograph.org.uk - 561906.jpg|thumb|300px|Looking east on Whitechapel Road, near [[Whitechapel station|Whitechapel tube station]]. The [[Whitechapel Road market|street market]] is on the left.]]
'''Whitechapel Road''' is a major [[arterial road]] in [[Whitechapel]], [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], in the [[East End of London]]. It is named after a small [[chapel of ease]] dedicated to [[St Mary]] and connects [[Aldgate]] to the west (as Whitechapel High Street) with [[Mile End Road]] to the east. The road is part of the historic [[Roman road]] from London to [[Colchester]], now the [[A11 road (Great Britain)|A11]].

The road had become built up by the 19th century and is now a main shopping district in the Whitechapel area. Along the road, there is an established [[Whitechapel Road market|market]], [[Whitechapel station]] and the [[Royal London Hospital]]. It remains an important road and is marked with [[bus lane]]s, with limited parking.

Several [[ethnic minority]] communities have centred on Whitechapel Road. The road was a focal point of the Jewish Community from the 1850s to the 1930s, with many Jewish shops and market stalls. Towards the latter part of the 20th century, the street became an established settlement of the [[British Bangladeshi]] community, who now sell a range of authentic Asian food and clothes in the market and on shop fronts. [[Altab Ali Park]] sits on the site of the original church at the western end of Whitechapel Road, and is a memorial to an Asian worker who suffered a fatal racial attack in 1978.

==Geography==
The road's name, along with the area, is derived from the original 14th century [[Whitechapel|White Chapel]].{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|p=1018}} It follows the section of the [[Roman roads in Britain|Roman road]] between [[Londinium]] ([[London]]) and [[Camulodunum]] ([[Colchester]]), which connected to the [[Pye Road]] to [[Venta Icenorum]] ([[Caistor St Edmund]] near [[Norwich]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://learninglegacy.independent.gov.uk/documents/pdfs/archaeology/ll35roman-road-aw.pdf|title=Learning Legacy: Lessons Learned from the London 2012 Games construction project|last=Chaffey|first=Gareth|publisher=Olympic Delivery Authority|date=2011|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> The section of the Roman road that is now Whitechapel Road is a [[Hierarchy of roads#primary route|Primary A-road]], the [[A11 road (Great Britain)|A11]], and has [[bus lane]]s running along its length.<ref name=tfl>{{cite web|url=https://consultations.tfl.gov.uk/cycling/89151b51|title=Section 2 – White Church Lane to Cambridge Heath Road|work=Barclays Superhighway 2|publisher=Transport for London|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> Owing to the popularity of the market, parking is heavily restricted, limited to occasional [[parking meter]]ed spaces along the road.{{sfn|Harriss|2006|p=121}}

[[List of cycle routes in London#Cycle Superhighways|Cycle Superhighway CS2]] runs along Whitechapel Road.<ref name=tfl/> The nearest [[London Underground]] stations are [[Whitechapel station]] and [[Aldgate East station]] and the nearest [[National Rail]] station is [[Bethnal Green railway station]]. A number of local [[London Buses]] routes run along Whitechapel Road, including 25, 205 and 254.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/cdn/static/cms/documents/bus-route-maps/north-east-london-bus-map.pdf|title=North to East London Bus Map|publisher=Transport for London|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref>

==History==
[[File:Whitechapel High Street 1905.JPG|right|thumb|180px|Whitechapel High Street in 1905]]
The road has been an important thoroughfare and coaching route for centuries. Whitechapel High Street and Whitechapel Road are named as such on [[John Rocque's Map of London, 1746]], both marked as "White Chapel".<ref>{{cite map|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:John_Rocque%27s_Map_of_London,_1746.png|via=Wikimedia|title=John Roque's Map of London|year=1746}}</ref> On [[John Cary]]'s "Environs of London" of 1795 (published in his ''New Itinerary'' of 1798) there are properties on both sides of the road.<ref name=cary>{{cite map|url=http://mapco.net/cary1795/cary15.htm|title=Cary's New And Accurate Plan of London And Westminster|year=1795|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> By the ninth edition in 1821, the road is shown as extensively built up.<ref>{{cite map|url=http://www.warwickleadlay.com/sites/default/files/styles/colorbox-fs/public/map_images/Cary-New-Itinerary-1821.jpg?itok=Oniix1iF|title=Environs of London|publisher=Cary's New Itinerary|year=1821|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> In the mid-19th century, [[droving|drovers]] steered livestock from local farms along the road towards [[Smithfield Market]], causing considerable [[traffic congestion]].{{sfn|Harriss|2006|p=121}}{{sfn|Davis|Emeljanow|2005|p=67}} By the 1870s, the road had become extensively developed with properties along the entire stretch of the road.{{sfn|Bard|2014|p=30}}

The [[Freedom Press]] Bookshop is on Angel Alley, No.&nbsp;84b Whitechapel High Street, and was established in the 1880s by Peter Kropotkin and Charlotte Wilson as the first publishing house to deal with [[anarchism]] and radical publications. The press has been controversial, and was fire-bombed in 2013, but quickly reopened.{{sfn|Harriss|2006|p=121}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/feb/04/freedom-press-oldest-radical-bookshop-arson-attack|title=Britain's oldest radical bookshop is burned, but the ideas survive|first=Tim|last=Gee|newspaper=The Guardian|date=4 February 2013|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> The [[Whitechapel Art Gallery]] on Whitechapel High Street opened in 1899. It was designed by Charles Harrison Townsend in 1895 and was the first major art gallery in East London. It has shown works of [[Jackson Pollock]], [[Robert Rauschenberg]] and [[David Hockney]]. It continues to be the centre of the arts scene in the area.{{sfn|Bracken|2011|p=18}}

[[File:St marys station 1938.jpg|thumb|left|[[St. Mary's (Whitechapel Road) tube station]] on Whitechapel Road, shortly after closure in 1938. The building was destroyed in 1940.]]
The [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]], a principal supplier of [[church bell]]s in Britain, was, until its closure in 2017, based at 32–34 Whitechapel Road.{{sfn|Harriss|2006|p=121}} The buildings date from 1670 and are [[listed building|Grade II listed]]. Originally a [[coaching inn]] known as the Artichoke, it was occupied by the foundry from 1738, replacing smaller premises on the north side of the road.{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|p=1018}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/foundry.htm|title=500 Years of History|publisher=Whitechapel Bell Foundry|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> [[Davenant Foundation School]] moved to No.&nbsp;173 Whitechapel Road in 1818. The school expanded with a new hall and classrooms in 1896, with further improvements in 1909. However, a decreasing child population meant that in 1965, the school moved to [[Loughton]], [[Essex]]. The building remains on the north side and is [[listed building|Grade II listed]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/middx/vol1/pp293-294|title=A History of the County of Middlesex|volume=1|publisher=Victoria County History|location=London|year=1969|pp=293–294}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://planreg.towerhamlets.gov.uk/WAM/doc/513588-Page-37.pdf?extension=.pdf&page=37&id=513588&contentType=application/pdf&location=VOLUME4|title=Townscape and Heritage|publisher=Tower Hamlets London Borough Council|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>

Continuing eastwards, Whitechapel station is on the north side of the road, alongside the [[Whitechapel Road market|street market]]. Behind the tube station is the former site of [[Blackwall Buildings]] a set of philanthropic houses built in 1890.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Administrative County of London development plan: first review 1960|publisher=London County Council|year=1962|p=192}}</ref> Just to the east of the market are [[almshouse]]s at Trinity House, that were originally built in 1695 for retired seamen.{{sfn|Harriss|2006|p=121}}

Nearby is the former site of [[St. Mary's (Whitechapel Road) tube station]]. It opened in March 1884 but its close proximity to both Whitechapel and [[Aldgate East station|Aldgate East]] tube stations made it superfluous, leading to its closure in April 1938.{{sfn|Bard|2014|p=133}} It was used as an air raid shelter in the [[Second World War]], but was destroyed by bombing in 1940.{{sfn|Long|2010|p=108}} Opposite to the south is the former [[Royal London Hospital]] building, built in 1740. The hospital suffered significant structural damage during the [[Second World War]], but much of the 18th and 19th centuries architecture still remains. A new building now sits adjacent to the original.{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|pp=725–726}}

[[File:Whitechapel Street Market.jpg|thumb|[[Whitechapel Road market]]]]
The [[Pavilion Theatre, Whitechapel|Pavilion Theatre]] opened on Nos.191–193&nbsp;Whitechapel Road, the site of a former clothes factory, in 1828. It was the first major theatre to open in the East End of London.{{sfn|Davis|Emeljanow|2005|p=55}} The original building was destroyed in a fire in 1856, and was replaced by a larger theatre that could accommodate over 1,000 people, becoming the centre of [[Yiddish theatre]] in Britain.{{sfn|Davis|Emeljanow|2005|p=58}} It closed in 1934.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ochjs.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/7th-Stencl-Lecture-Memories-of-London-Yiddish-Theatre.pdf|title=Memories of London Yiddish Theatre|publisher=Oxford Centre for Postgraduate Hebrew Studies|date=14 August 1989|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref>

During the 1940s, the Metropolitan Police attempted to crack down on illegal gambling held in social clubs along Whitechapel Road. The Brancroft Social Club was based at No.&nbsp;69,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/33793/page/580/data.pdf|title=Advertisement of Cancelling|publisher=The London Gazette|date=26 January 1932|p=580|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> and in March 1944, a police raid uncovered unlicensed horse and dog race betting which led to the arrest of the club's owner and 21 patrons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1944/apr/04/club-raids-london#S5CV0398P0_19440404_HOC_240|title=Club Raids, London|work=Hansard|date=4 April 1944|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref>

The [[Albion Brewery]] was first established at the eastern end of Whitechapel Road in 1808 by Richard Ivory, landlord of [[the Blind Beggar]]. In 1860, the brewery was rebuilt, producing an average of 133,000 barrels of beer a year. It closed in 1979.{{sfn|Richmond|Turton|1990|pp=224–225}}

The [[E postcode area|Eastern District Post Office]] is based at the eastern end of Whitechapel Road, on the south side. This was the eastern terminus for the former [[London Post Office Railway]] (colloquially known as the "Mail Rail"), built to allow fast mail transfers across London. It closed in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1913/jun/11/post-office-london-railway-bill|title=Post Office (London) Railway Bill|date=11 June 1913|work=Hansard|first=Herbert|last=Samuel|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-25145632|title=Mail Rail: What is it like on the 'secret' tube|first=Andy|last=Dangerfield|work=BBC News|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>  Beyond this is Mile End Gate – where the road becomes [[Mile End Road]]; and was the site of the former [[toll gate]].<ref name=cary/>

==Community==
[[File:Aerial view of East London Mosque complex - Feb 2014.jpg|thumb|left|The [[East London Mosque]] has been established on Whitechapel Road since 1985.]]
The road has the been the centre of several [[ethnic minority]] groups in London. In the 1840s, many Irish emigrated to avoid the [[Irish potato famine|potato famine]] and began street selling at Whitechapel Market and along Whitechapel Road.{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|p=1017}}

The [[History of the Jews in England|Jewish community]] settled on and around Whitechapel Road from the 1850s onwards.{{sfn|Snyder|2013|p=105}} In the 1880s, the community expanded rapidly as [[Ashkenazi Jews]] fled to Britain and took over many of the shops and market stalls on the street.{{sfn|Moore|2003|p=296}} For the remainder of the century and much of the 20th, the road was the focal point of the community. The nearby [[Jewish Free School]] was, at one point, the largest educational establishment in the world, with over 4,300 pupils.{{sfn|Moore|2003|p=296}} A fountain opposite the Royal London Hospital in memory of [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|King Edward VII]] has the inscription "erected from subscriptions raised by Jewish inhabitants of East London".{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|p=1018}} On 4 October 1936, [[British Union of Fascists]] leader [[Oswald Mosley]] organised an anti-Jewish parade through the East End that included passing through Whitechapel Road, but was stopped by a crowd of protesters.{{sfn|Moore|2003|p=297}} The sentiment against Jews in Whitechapel Road caused the community to dissolve from the 1930s onwards; the Pavilion Theatre closed and the Jewish Free School was destroyed in [[the Blitz]] during the Second World War.{{sfn|Moore|2003|p=298}} The Yiddish newspaper ''The Jewish Times'' (''Die Zeit'') was produced at No.&nbsp;135 Whitechapel Road from 1913 to 1936.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2lgpAQAAIAAJ|title=Willing's Press Guide|publisher=T Skinner Directories|p=68|year=1967}}</ref>

Towards the end of the 20th century, the street, along with nearby [[Brick Lane]] became the centre of the [[British Bangladeshi|British Bangladeshi community]]. The [[East London Mosque]] on Whitechapel Road was opened by Shaykh Abdullah bin Subayl in 1985 and can accommodate over 3,000 worshippers, with dedicated facilities for women. The nearby [[London Muslim Centre]] opened in 2003.{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|p=1018}} Whitechapel Market caters well for the community, with stalls stocking Asian fruit and vegetables including [[okra]] and [[mango]]es, clothing such as tunics and [[pashmina]]s, and [[mobile phone]] cards for cheap long-distance calls.{{sfn|Harriss|2006|pp=121–122}} A racially motivated attack on local worker Altab Ali near Whitechapel Road in May 1978 was a significant event for the local Asian community, and his life is now commemorated in [[Altab Ali Park]] at the western end of the road, which was built on the former St Mary's Church grounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/news/altab_ali_s_racist_murder_in_whitechapel_remembered_37_years_on_1_4061835|title=Altab Ali's racist murder in Whitechapel remembered 37 years on|work=East London Advertiser|first=Mike|last=Brooke|date=6 May 2015|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Moore|2003|p=303}}

==Events==
[[File:The blind beggar 1.jpg|thumb|upright|[[The Blind Beggar]] public house, 337 Whitechapel Road]]
The area around Whitechapel Road is notorious for the 19th century [[Whitechapel murders]], which are believed to be linked to [[Jack the Ripper]]. One of the first victims was [[Martha Tabram]], who was found with multiple stab wounds on George Yard Buildings, Whitechapel Road on 7 August 1888.{{sfn|Hibbert|Weinreb|2010|p=1017}}

[[Joseph Merrick]], the Elephant Man, moved to Whitechapel Road in 1884. Visitors paid to see him in the back room of a shop owned by showman [[Tom Norman]]. The shop was directly opposite the Royal London Hospital, and Merrick was frequently visited by doctors.{{sfn|Howell|Ford|1992|pp=72,75}} Merrick later moved to the hospital permanently, where he spent the last years of his life.{{sfn|Moore|2003|p=294}}

The Blind Beggar is at No.&nbsp;337 and was the founding point of the [[Salvation Army]] following a meeting outside the pub by [[William Booth]] in 1865. On 9 March 1966, the venue became notorious after [[Ronnie Kray]] fatally shot [[George Cornell]] at the pub. The premises remains open for business, though it has been refurbished several times.{{sfn|Sullivan|2000|p=26}} The Kray Twins also used the Blackwall Buildings, by then [[urban decay|dilapidated]], as a form of punishment by locking a victim in a flat alone with Ronnie's [[German Shepherd]] dog.{{sfn|Pearson|2011|p=2280}}

==Cultural references==
Whitechapel Road is the equal cheapest property location on the British version of the [[Monopoly (game)|Monopoly]] game board. Both it and the [[Old Kent Road]] are priced at £60. In reality, increasing property prices across London meant that the average house price on Whitechapel Road in 2013 was £295,082.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/news/10145168/Real-life-prices-on-Monopoly-board-revealed.html|title=Real life prices on Monopoly Board revealed|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>

